\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. X. strumarium} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 987 (1753). Stem 20-120 cm, sometimes more, usually branched, unarmed. Leaves long-petiolate; lamina broadly ovate to triangular, with a cordate or rarely cuneate base, entire, or with 3-5 wide, coarsely serrate lobes, green and with short, stiff hairs on both surfaces. Capitula in axillary clusters and sometimes also in a terminal, leafless inflorescence, the male above the female. Involucre in fruit with straight or hooked spines and distinct beaks.{\i  River-banks, lake shores, pastures and disturbed ground. E., C. & S. Europe; casual in the north and west. }Al Au Az Bl Bu Co Cr Cz Ga Ge Gr He Hs Hu It Ju Lu Po Rm Rs (B, C, W, K, E) Sa Si Tu.
