\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 51.            Heliopsis}            Pers.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc By A. Hansen.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Perennials. Leaves opposite. Capitula solitary, large. Involucral bracts in 2-3 rows. Receptacle conical, with numerous scales. Ligulate florets in 1 row, female, yellow. Tubular florets hermaphrodite. Achenes obtusely 3- to 4-angled; pappus absent or a small, more or less toothed rim.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Literature: T. R. Fisher, {\i Ohio Jour. Sci.}{\b  57}: 171-191 (1957).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. H. helianthoides} (L.) Sweet,{\i  Hort. Brit.} 487 (1827). Stems 30-150 cm, simple or branched. Leaves lanceolate to deltate-ovate, smooth or scabrid, coarsely serrate or dentate, petiolate. Peduncles 10-25 cm; involucral bracts ovate-lanceolate, the outer usually leaf-like. Ligules c. 25 × 6 mm. Achenes 3-3·5 mm, glabrous, truncate, those of the ligules 3-angled, those of the tubular florets 4-angled above, rounded below.{\i  Cultivated for ornament and locally naturalized in Europe.} [Da Ge Hu Po.] ({\i North America.})
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b scabra} (Dunal) Fisher,{\i  Ohio Jour. Sci.}{\b  57}: 190 (1957): Leaves lanceolate to ovate-lanceolate; petioles 2-2·5 cm. Disc of capitulum 12-14 mm.{\i  Scattered throughout the European range of the species}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b occidentalis} Fisher, {\i op. cit.} 189 (1957): Leaves deltate-ovate; petioles not more than 1·5 cm. Disc of capitulum 15-25 mm.{\i  Scattered throughout the European range of the species}.
\par

